We’re so excited to announce Matilda’s Reading List! Readers across the U.S. sent in their reading recommendations for Roald Dahl’s iconic bookworm, Matilda! Here are the final six recommendations, chosen by kids around the country, that celebrate the power and potential of young people to change their stories.

📚 FRONT DESK By Kelly Yang

“I really liked this book and that it was inspired by the Author's own childhood. It is very dark in places and heart-breaking, but also has hope. Although it’s a completely different story to Matilda's, I think Mia, like Matilda, is brave, strong and stands up for what’s right. She is a determined young girl.  Matilda and Mia have similar traits in how they see the world and how they want it to be better and try to make it better.” – Alisha Weir, 12, star of Roald Dahl’s Matilda the Musical

📚 WHEN STARS ARE SCATTERED by Omar Mohamed and Victoria Jamieson

📚 PAGES & CO: The Bookwanderers by Anna James, illustrated by Paola Escobar 

📚 AMARI AND THE NIGHT BROTHERS by B. B. Alston

📚 SMALL SPACES by Katherine Arden

📚 CHANGE SINGS: A Children’s Anthem by Amanda Gorman, Illustrated by Loren Long

⭐️ Teachers! ⭐️ Announcing a FREE Student Writing Publishing Opportunity for your classroom! 

There’s no more magical feeling than seeing yourself in a book—your hopes and dreams, your struggles and triumphs reflected! It’s the most empowering feeling in the world, which is why I wrote FINALLY SEEN, my newest middle grade out next month! 👀 Ahead of the launch, I’m inviting kids from all over America to tell me…

What book makes YOU feel FINALLY SEEN?

In 200 words or less, tell me your experience connecting with a book, whether that book is a mirror or a sliding glass door! What was it like? What book was it? How did it change your life? Enter on my website! 🤩

Visit Kellyyang.com for full details! Open to all classrooms in the USA and homeschooled kids, under 18 years old! Limit 5 submissions per classroom! Oh and I’ll be raffling off 30 free copies of FINALLY SEEN to participating classrooms!!!

I can’t wait to read your writing and HAVE FUN! ❤️📚 #FinallySeen @SimonKIDS

Just a mom, sitting in a school parking lot, wondering why….why can’t we stop the tyranny of gun violence?? 😭

FINALLY SEEN has been on the @nytimes Bestsellers List for a full month and I have some words. I hope my “quietly fierce” book about book banning lights a fire in us all! Enough is enough! Stop banning books & actually solve REAL PROBLEMS! Not phony, made up problems for the sake of fostering hate, erasing people & robbing public education. But real problems, like keeping our children alive! 

Let’s stop the senseless book bashing and FINALLY SEE kids, what they’re going through, what they need, and do right by them!

That’s my greatest hope for this book. For my career. For my life. ❤️

Thank you to everyone for supporting this book and giving my writing a chance— I am so overwhelmed with gratitude! I love you so much!! You give me fuel and light every day!

#FinallySeen #BeLoud #BeBrave #BeSeen @simonkids

We're excited! Award-winning and bestselling author @kellyyanghk will join us as honorary chair for #NationalLibraryWeek, April 23-29, 2023. 
There's More to the Story. Follow the Link in our bio to read the press release.

"As a young immigrant child, I came to this country when I was six years old with no English. I know firsthand that there’s so much more to the story when it comes to libraries, just like there’s more to my story. I am the product of amazing libraries and librarians, who saw me, supported me, and nurtured me. Through books, movies, games, giveaways, and engaging programming, I found the courage to go for my dreams." Kelly Yang, Honorary Chair. National Library Week, April 23-29, 2023. Happy Day 5 of #AANHPIHeritageMonth! It’s time for another edition of #FridaysWithMia where my 13yo niece reads and reviews a middle grade/YA book for us. Here’s Mia!

// The fourth book in the Front Desk series is just as incredible (and maybe more so) than the others! Mia Tang is excited because it’s the Women’s World Cup—and China and the US are the final two teams! The only problem is that she doesn’t know who she’s supposed to be cheering for. Both teams are a part of who she is—and everyone is telling her she has to choose a side. Why should she? 

Also, Mr. Yao is attempting to be a part of the motel again as a co-owner, and Mia is wary of his real intentions. Last time he was in charge, things were not all that great. Has he changed since then? On top of that, her PE teacher has given her a C for her less-than-convincing attempt at sports,  and the only way to fix it is to get interviews with the champion teams. How is she supposed to do that? It’s going to take a miracle to get through all that—but Mia is determined to succeed at everything. But that’s one massive load to deal with. Can Mia Tang write her way out of this one? 

I read this book in one, perfect sitting. It’s books like these that turn people into readers, that make you happy and confident and help you believe that you can accomplish anything. The character arcs are amazing- especially Mr. Yao’s in this book. Second chances and redemption are a part of life and they are illustrated so perfectly in this book. Each and every character has their own special qualities and personalities that make you want to meet them in real life. 

You may not be in this book, but you’ll feel as if you’re there with Mia, Lupe, and Jason as they navigate the difficulties of middle school, and as Mia’s family attempts to buy a house of their own! I absolutely love everything this book stands for and represents—it’s one-of-a-kind and heart-breakingly realistic, because all of the best books are. //

Thank you, Mia! And thank you, @kellyyanghk. [ID: Key Player resting on rumpled green fabric]

When ten-year-old Lina Gao sees her mom’s video on social media take off, she’s captivated by the potential to be seen and heard! Maybe online she can finally find the confidence she craves. Whereas in real life she’s growing so fast, she feels like microwave popcorn, bursting out of her skin!

With the help of her two best friends, Carla and Finn, and her little sister, Millie, Lina sets off to go viral. Except there’s a lot more to social media than Lina ever imagined, like:

1. Seeing inside her classmates’ lives! Is she really the only person on the planet who doesn’t have a walk-in closet?
2. Group chats! Disappearing videos! What is everyone talking about in the secret chats? And how can she join?
3. A bazillion stories about what to eat, wear, and put on her face. Could they all be telling the truth? Everyone sounds so sure of what they’re saying!

As Lina descends deeper and deeper into social media, it will take all her strength to break free from the likes and find the courage to be her authentic self in this fast-paced world. 

Out 2/27/24! 🔥 This is the sequel to FINALLY SEEN, but can be read as a stand-alone! Ideally read BEFORE kids get a phone! I learned so much about social media while researching and writing this book and I am so hoping that Lina’s story will lead to much needed convos about our digital health! ❤️ Also, can we just gush over @maike_illu’s beautiful cover?? 😍 Preorder now! @simonkids #FinallyHeard #FinallySeen #SocialMedia #Kids
